        },
        {
          "title": "Practical mechanics of doing Kometz and Levona separately versus together",
          "display_title": "Separate vs Together",
          "timestamp": "02:39"
        }
      ]
    },
    {
      "title": "The three-way debate on Lehanniach (leaving over) and its status in Pigul law",
      "display_title": "Lehanniach Status",
      "timestamp": "05:06",
      "micro_segments": [
        {
          "title": "Tanna Kamma's position: Lehanniach is not a concern even according to Rabbi Eliezer",
          "display_title": "Tanna Kamma",
          "timestamp": "05:06"
        },
        {
          "title": "Rabbi Yehuda's position: Lehanniach is Pasul according to everyone",
          "display_title": "Rabbi Yehuda",
          "timestamp": "06:01"
        },
        {
          "title": "The Gezeira from leaving over all blood (Kol Damo) as proof for Rabbi Yehuda's view",
          "display_title": "Kol Damo Gezeira",
          "timestamp": "06:18"
        },
        {
          "title": "Rav Elazar's position: Lehanniach is debated like other Pigul issues",
          "display_title": "Rav Elazar",
          "timestamp": "09:51"
        }
      ]
    },
    {
      "title": "The narrative of Yosef HaBavli learning from Rabbi Elazar ben Shamua about Lehanniach",
      "display_title": "Yosef HaBavli Story",
      "timestamp": "16:16",
      "micro_segments": [
        {
          "title": "Yosef HaBavli's question to Rabbi Elazar ben Shamua and the repeated answer of Kasher",
          "display_title": "Repeated Kasher Answers",
          "timestamp": "16:16"
        },
        {
          "title": "The revelation that Rabbi Eliezer disputes and rules Pasul on Lehanniach",
          "display_title": "Rabbi Eliezer Dispute",
          "timestamp": "17:24"
        },
        {
          "title": "Yosef's explanation: he learned from Rabbi Yehuda and sought corroboration",
          "display_title": "Yosef's Explanation",
          "timestamp": "18:32"
        },
        {
          "title": "Rabbi Elazar's emotional response and connection to Rabbi Eliezer's tradition",
          "display_title": "Emotional Response",
          "timestamp": "19:58"
        },
        {
          "title": "Resolution: Rabbi Yehuda transmitted Rabbi Eliezer's position as an alternative view",
          "display_title": "Transmission Resolved",
          "timestamp": "21:02"
        }
      ]
    },
    {
      "title": "The Gemara's analysis of Rabbi Yehuda's implicit claim that everyone (Divrei HaKol) agrees on Lehanniach being Pasul",
      "display_title": "Divrei HaKol Analysis",
      "timestamp": "22:19",
      "micro_segments": [
        {
          "title": "Gemara challenges: If Divrei HaKol Pasul, why did Yosef say his lost object was returned?",
          "display_title": "Lost Object Problem",
          "timestamp": "22:19"
        },
        {
          "title": "Gemara's resolution: Rabbi Yehuda explicitly claims Divrei HaKol Pasul, not just a Machloket",
          "display_title": "Explicit Divrei HaKol",
          "timestamp": "26:38"
        }
      ]
    },
    {
      "title": "The Mishna's list of Mincha preparation defects that do not invalidate the offering",
      "display_title": "Mincha Defects List",
      "timestamp": "30:22",
      "micro_segments": [
        {
          "title": "Lo Yatzak (no pouring): whether it means no Yetzika at all or a non-Kohen did it",
          "display_title": "Lo Yatzak",
          "timestamp": "30:22"
        },
        {
          "title": "Lo Balal (no mixing): literal meaning and the Mishna's implicit assumption that Belila is not Me'akev",
          "display_title": "Lo Balal",
          "timestamp": "31:23"
        },
        {
          "title": "Other defects: Lo Patit, Lo Malach, Lo Henif, Lo Higish, Lo Mashach - all Kasher",
          "display_title": "Other Defects",
          "timestamp": "31:33"
        }
      ]
    },
    {
      "title": "The Gemara's clarification that Yetzika is Me'akev and the Mishna's interpretation",
      "display_title": "Yetzika Me'akev",
      "timestamp": "34:26",
      "micro_segments": [
        {
          "title": "Gemara asks: if Lo Yatzak means no Yetzika at all, how is it Kasher when Yetzika is Me'akev?",
          "display_title": "Yetzika Required",
          "timestamp": "34:26"
        },
        {
          "title": "Gemara answers: Lo Yatzak means a non-Kohen did the Yetzika, not that it wasn't done at all",
          "display_title": "Non-Kohen Yetzika",
          "timestamp": "35:46"
        },
        {
          "title": "Support from Tosefta in Zevachim that Lo Balal teaches Belila is not always Me'akev",
          "display_title": "Tosefta Support",
          "timestamp": "36:57"
        }
      ]
    },
    {
      "title": "The Mishna's list of Mincha preparation defects that do not invalidate the offering (continued)",
      "display_title": "Mincha Defects List…",
      "timestamp": "39:26",
      "micro_segments": [
        {
          "title": "The principle Kol HaRaui L'Blila Ein Blila Me'akevet Bo: fitness for mixing versus actual mixing",
          "display_title": "Fitness for Mixing",
          "timestamp": "39:26"
        },
        {
          "title": "Ptitim Merubot (excessive breaking): whether large or numerous pieces invalidate",
          "display_title": "Ptitim Merubot",
          "timestamp": "46:04"
        }
      ]
    },
    {
      "title": "Rabbi Shimon's view that all Mincha preparation requires a Kohen and the distinction between Minchat Yisrael and Minchat Kohanim",
      "display_title": "Rabbi Shimon Position",
      "timestamp": "49:05",
      "micro_segments": [
        {
          "title": "Rabbi Shimon: one who doesn't agree to perform Avoda has no portion in Kehuna",
          "display_title": "Rabbi Shimon's View",
          "timestamp": "49:05"
        },
        {
          "title": "The fifteen Avodot of Kohanim including Yetzika, Blila, and Ptita",
          "display_title": "Fifteen Avodot",
          "timestamp": "50:54"
        },
        {
          "title": "Rav Nachman's resolution: Minchat Yisrael (with Kmitza) can use a Zar; Minchat Kohanim (no Kmitza) requires a Kohen",
          "display_title": "Rav Nachman's Resolution",
          "timestamp": "53:39"
        },
        {
          "title": "Rava's objection: Yetzika is learned from Minchat Yisrael, so a Zar should work in all cases",
          "display_title": "Rava's Objection",
          "timestamp": "54:54"
        },
        {
          "title": "Rav Soloveitchik's insight on Kohanim being defined by intrinsic Kedusha, not specific roles",
          "display_title": "Kedusha Analysis",
          "timestamp": "56:31"
        }
      ]
    }
